President Barack Obama has proclaimed December as National Impaired Driving Prevention Month. The proclamation highlights the dangers of drunk, drugged, and distracted driving, emphasizing the need for safe driving practices and responsible decision-making. The president urges Americans to take appropriate measures to prevent impaired driving, including avoiding drug use and distractions while behind the wheel. The administration has implemented a ban on texting while driving for federal employees and supports campaigns to raise awareness and detect impaired drivers. The proclamation calls for the collective efforts of individuals, families, businesses, and community organizations to promote substance abuse prevention and make America's roadways safer.